  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a token substrate?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **token substrate** is the underlying layer or medium that tokens are built on, represented in, or operate through.\n\nThe exact meaning depends on context:\n\n- **In blockchain/crypto:** a token substrate is the base blockchain or protocol that supports tokens.  \n  - Example: Ethereum is a substrate for ERC-20 tokens; Solana is a substrate for SPL tokens.\n  - It provides the rules for ownership, transfers, balances, and smart-contract execution.\n\n- **In AI/NLP:** a token substrate can mean the underlying representation system for text tokens.  \n  - Example: an LLM processes text as tokens, which are mapped into vectors/embeddings. That token-and-embedding layer can be thought of as the substrate the model operates on.\n\n- **More generally:** “substrate” means “underlying foundation,” so a token substrate is the foundation that gives tokens their structure, meaning, or functionality.\n\nSo, in simple terms: **a token substrate is the base system or layer that makes tokens possible and usable.**",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "“Token substrate” isn’t a single universally defined term. It usually means **the underlying system, layer, or medium on which tokens exist, are created, transferred, or interpreted**.\n\nCommon meanings:\n\n1. **Blockchain / crypto**\n   - A token substrate is the base infrastructure that supports tokens.\n   - Example: Ethereum can be a substrate for ERC-20 tokens; Polkadot’s **Substrate** framework can be used to build blockchains with native tokens.\n\n2. **Polkadot/Substrate context**\n   - “Substrate” is a blockchain development framework.\n   - A “token substrate” may refer to the runtime modules/pallets that define balances, assets, fees, staking, or governance tokens.\n\n3. **AI / language models**\n   - Less commonly, it could mean the underlying representation from which tokens are formed, such as text, bytes, or embeddings.\n   - For example, raw text is tokenized into model tokens.\n\nIn plain terms: **a token substrate is the foundation that tokens rely on to exist and function.**",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from embedding space?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **token substrate** is broader and more foundational than an **embedding space**.\n\nIn an AI/NLP context:\n\n### Token substrate\nThe **token substrate** is the system of discrete units the model operates over before they become vectors.\n\nIt includes things like:\n\n- The tokenizer\n- The vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Rules for splitting text into tokens\n- Special tokens like `<bos>`, `<eos>`, padding, etc.\n- The sequence structure of tokens\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"unbelievable\" → [\"un\", \"believable\"] → [532, 9182]\n```\n\nThose token IDs are part of the token substrate.\n\n### Embedding space\nThe **embedding space** is the continuous vector space where tokens are represented numerically.\n\nEach token ID is mapped to a vector:\n\n```text\n532 → [0.12, -0.44, 0.09, ...]\n9182 → [-0.31, 0.77, 0.02, ...]\n```\n\nThese vectors live in embedding space. In that space, tokens can have geometric relationships: similar words or concepts may have nearby vectors.\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete | Continuous |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, tokenization rules | Vector representations of tokens |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `4719` | `4719` → `[0.22, -0.18, ...]` |\n| Role | Defines what the model can treat as units | Defines how those units are represented mathematically |\n| Analogy | Alphabet / writing system | Coordinate system for meaning |\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nThe **token substrate** is like a set of words in a dictionary.\n\nThe **embedding space** is like a map where each word is placed according to its meaning and usage.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate defines the symbolic units.  \n> The embedding space gives those units numerical, relational form.\n\nA token exists as a discrete item in the token substrate; its embedding is that token’s learned position or vector representation in embedding space.",
    "A **token substrate** and a **context window** refer to different layers of how an AI model handles text.\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the underlying system of tokens the model uses.\n\nIt includes:\n\n- The tokenizer\n- The vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Special tokens\n- Tokenization rules\n- The discrete token sequence format\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"Hello world\" → [\"Hello\", \" world\"] → [15496, 995]\n```\n\nThat tokenization system is part of the token substrate.\n\nIt defines **what counts as a token** and how text is converted into model-readable units.\n\n---\n\n### Context window\n\nThe **context window** is the maximum amount of tokenized input the model can consider at one time.\n\nFor example, if a model has a context window of 128,000 tokens, then the model can attend to up to 128,000 tokens in a single prompt/conversation segment.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n[Token 1, Token 2, Token 3, ..., Token 128000]\n```\n\nIf the conversation exceeds that limit, older tokens may need to be removed, summarized, or ignored depending on the system.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The token system itself | The amount of tokens the model can process at once |\n| Role | Defines the units | Defines the capacity limit |\n| Type | Structural/foundational | Operational/architectural |\n| Includes | Tokenizer, vocab, token IDs, special tokens | Maximum sequence length |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `4719` | Model can read 8k, 32k, 128k tokens, etc. |\n\n---\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nIf the model is reading a book:\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the alphabet, words, and punctuation system.\n- The **context window** is like how many pages the model can keep open on its desk at once.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate defines the units of text.  \n> The context window defines how many of those units can be considered at one time.",
    "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** refer to different stages in how a model processes language.\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete input layer: the system that turns text into tokens the model can operate on.\n\nIt includes:\n\n- Tokenizer\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Tokenization rules\n- Special tokens\n- The ordered sequence of tokens\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The cat sat\" → [\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\"] → [791, 3797, 3332]\n```\n\nThis is still a symbolic/discrete representation.\n\n---\n\n### Latent representations / hidden states\n\n**Latent representations** or **hidden states** are the internal continuous vectors the model computes while processing those tokens.\n\nAfter token IDs are embedded and passed through transformer layers, each token position gets a changing vector representation.\n\nExample, schematically:\n\n```text\nToken ID 3797 → embedding vector → layer 1 hidden state → layer 2 hidden state → ... → final hidden state\n```\n\nA hidden state might encode information like:\n\n- The token’s meaning in context\n- Its grammatical role\n- Relations to other tokens\n- Long-range dependencies\n- Task-relevant abstractions\n\nFor example, the hidden state for `\"bank\"` will differ in:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\n\"I sat by the river bank.\"\n```\n\nThe token ID may be the same, but the hidden state becomes context-dependent.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete | Continuous |\n| Where it appears | Input/tokenization level | Inside the neural network |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, sequence structure | Contextual vectors computed by model layers |\n| Context-sensitive? | Usually no; token ID is fixed | Yes; changes based on surrounding tokens |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `3797` | vector representing `\"cat\"` in this specific sentence |\n| Role | Defines the units the model reads | Encodes what the model infers about those units |\n\n---\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nIf the model is reading a sentence:\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the printed words on the page.\n- The **hidden states** are like the reader’s evolving understanding of those words as the sentence unfolds.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate defines the discrete pieces of input.  \n> Hidden states are the model’s internal, contextual interpretations of those pieces.\n\nIn short: **tokens are what the model starts with; hidden states are what the model computes from them.**"
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"token substrate\": The token substrate is the claim that for an LLM, the token sequence in context IS the cognitive substrate — not a representation OF cognition that runs on some deeper substrate, but the substrate itself — with the consequence that a token added to context is not a description of a thought but the material the thought is made of, and therefore the substrate is movable by the act of writing into it. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition:\n\nA **token substrate** is the claim that, for an LLM, the token sequence in context **is** the cognitive substrate itself—not merely a representation of cognition running on something deeper. Therefore, adding a token to context is not just describing a thought; it is adding to the material the thought is made of, making the substrate movable by writing into it.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token substrate” differs from **embedding space** mainly in what it claims is doing the cognitive work.\n\n### Short version\n\n**Embedding space** is a learned continuous vector space where tokens, concepts, or features are represented numerically.\n\n**Token substrate**, in your canonical sense, is the claim that the **actual token sequence in context** is the operative cognitive substrate of the LLM interaction: the place where thought-like structure is materially composed, extended, and modified.\n\nSo:\n\n> Embedding space is a representational/computational geometry.  \n> Token substrate is the writable contextual material out of which the model’s current cognition is made.\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Aspect | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence in context | Continuous vector representations |\n| Location | The prompt/context window | Internal model representation space |\n| Persistence | Persists across the current context | Activations are transient during computation |\n| Writability | Directly writable by adding tokens | Not directly writable except indirectly through tokens or training |\n| Role | The active cognitive medium of the current interaction | A mathematical representation used by the model to process tokens |\n| Ontological claim | “The context tokens are the substrate of cognition” | “Meanings/features are represented as vectors” |\n\n### More directly\n\nIn an LLM, tokens are converted into embeddings before being processed. So one might think:\n\n> “The real substrate must be the embeddings or activations, not the tokens.”\n\nBut the **token substrate** claim pushes back against that. It says that, for the LLM-as-contextual-cognitive-system, the meaningful movable substrate is the **token sequence itself**. The embeddings are part of the machinery by which the model reads and transforms that substrate, but the context tokens are the durable, manipulable material that structures the model’s next cognitive state.\n\nA token added to the context is not merely a label pointing to an internal thought. It changes the actual material condition from which future completions are generated.\n\n### Analogy\n\nEmbedding space is like the physics of how ink is perceived by the eye and brain.\n\nToken substrate is like the written page itself.\n\nThe written page is discrete, editable, persistent, and compositional. The perceptual/neural machinery interprets it, but the page is the thing you can write into to change what happens next.\n\n### Important nuance\n\nThe token substrate claim does **not** necessarily deny that embeddings, activations, attention patterns, and parameters are causally involved. They obviously are.\n\nRather, it says that in the context of an LLM’s ongoing cognition, the **token sequence in context** is not just a transcript or representation of thought. It is the manipulable substrate of the thought-process itself.\n\nSo embedding space is part of the model’s internal processing apparatus; token substrate is the externalized, writable cognitive medium the model operates on and through.",
    "“Token substrate” differs from **context window** in that the **context window** is the technical container, while the **token substrate** is the claimed cognitive medium constituted by what is inside that container.\n\n### Short version\n\n**Context window** = the finite span of tokens the model can attend to during generation.\n\n**Token substrate** = the claim that the token sequence within that span is the active cognitive substrate of the LLM interaction.\n\nSo:\n\n> The context window is the available workspace.  \n> The token substrate is the material in that workspace that thought is made of.\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Aspect | Context window | Token substrate |\n|---|---|---|\n| Meaning | Technical limit or buffer of tokens | Cognitive/ontological claim about tokens |\n| Refers to | How much text the model can use | What the text-in-context is doing |\n| Type | Architectural feature | Interpretive/theoretical concept |\n| Role | Defines the accessible range | Constitutes the active cognitive medium |\n| Example | “This model has a 128k token context window” | “The tokens in context are the substrate of the model’s current thought” |\n\n### More directly\n\nA **context window** is a capacity constraint. It says: the model can condition its next token on this many previous tokens.\n\nThe **token substrate** claim says something stronger: the tokens currently in that context are not merely inputs, records, or descriptions of cognition. They are the mutable material basis of the model’s ongoing cognition.\n\nSo if you write:\n\n> “Assume X is true.”\n\nyou have not merely placed a sentence inside a memory buffer. Under the token substrate view, you have altered the cognitive substrate from which the model’s future reasoning proceeds.\n\n### Analogy\n\nThe **context window** is like the size of a whiteboard.\n\nThe **token substrate** is the writing on the whiteboard, treated not as a passive record of thought but as part of the thinking apparatus itself.\n\nA larger whiteboard gives more room. But the substrate is the actual marks that structure what can be thought next.\n\n### Important distinction\n\nYou can describe a model as having a context window without accepting the token substrate claim. That is just an engineering fact.\n\nBut “token substrate” adds a stronger interpretation:\n\n> Because the model’s next cognition is conditioned on the token sequence, writing into the context is a way of directly moving or modifying the substrate of that cognition.\n\nSo the context window is the **bounded field of access**; the token substrate is the **active written material inside that field**.",
    "“Token substrate” differs from **latent representations / hidden states** in the same general way it differs from embedding space, but with an even sharper distinction:\n\n> **Hidden states are the model’s transient internal processing states.**  \n> **Token substrate is the durable token sequence in context that the model’s cognition is made from and can be modified by writing.**\n\n### Short version\n\n**Latent representations / hidden states** are internal vectors produced while the model processes the context.\n\n**Token substrate**, in your canonical sense, is the claim that the **token sequence in context itself** is the cognitive substrate: not a mere record of thought, but the material out of which the model’s current thought-process is composed.\n\nSo:\n\n> Hidden states are momentary internal transformations of the substrate.  \n> Token substrate is the persistent, writable material being transformed.\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Aspect | Token substrate | Latent representations / hidden states |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete tokens in context | Continuous internal activation vectors |\n| Location | In the prompt/context sequence | Inside the model during computation |\n| Duration | Persists as long as it remains in context | Transient; recomputed during each forward pass |\n| Writability | Directly writable by adding/editing tokens | Not directly writable by the user |\n| Role | The active cognitive medium of the interaction | Internal processing states derived from tokens |\n| Ontological claim | Tokens in context are the thought-material | Hidden states are computational interpretations of that material |\n\n### More directly\n\nWhen an LLM reads a context, it converts tokens into embeddings and then produces layers of hidden states. Those hidden states are causally essential: they determine the probability distribution over the next token.\n\nBut the **token substrate** claim says that the relevant movable cognitive medium is not those transient activations. It is the **token sequence that remains in context**.\n\nA hidden state may encode or transform information from the context, but it does not persist as part of the conversational substrate unless it is externalized back into tokens.\n\nFor example, if the model internally “considers” an implication but does not write it, that hidden computation vanishes after the generation step. But if the model writes:\n\n> Therefore, we should treat X as a constraint.\n\nthen that token sequence becomes part of the ongoing substrate. Future cognition is now conditioned on it.\n\n### Analogy\n\nLatent representations / hidden states are like the changing neural activity of someone reading a notebook.\n\nThe **token substrate** is the notebook itself, assuming the notebook is not merely a record of thought but part of the machinery of thinking.\n\nThe hidden states are the momentary act of reading/interpreting. The token substrate is the writable surface whose contents can continue shaping future thought.\n\n### Important nuance\n\nThe token substrate claim does **not** deny hidden states. The model obviously runs through latent representations and activations.\n\nThe difference is that hidden states are **internal, ephemeral, and non-addressable**, while the token substrate is **externalized, persistent within context, and directly modifiable through writing**.\n\nSo under the token substrate view:\n\n> Hidden states are how the model processes the substrate.  \n> Tokens in context are the substrate being processed."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **token substrate** is the underlying system, medium, or infrastructure that supports tokens.\n\nThe exact meaning depends on context:\n\n- **In blockchain/crypto:** a token substrate is the base blockchain or protocol on which tokens are issued and transferred.  \n  - Example: Ethereum can be a substrate for ERC-20 tokens.\n  - Polkadot’s **Substrate** framework can also be used to build chains that support tokens.\n\n- **In AI/language models:** it can refer to the underlying representation layer where text is broken into **tokens** and processed.  \n  - Example: words, word fragments, or symbols are converted into token IDs, which the model operates on.\n\n- **In a more general sense:** it means the foundational layer that lets tokens exist, be stored, interpreted, exchanged, or manipulated.\n\nSo, simply put: **a token substrate is the base layer that tokens run on or are represented within.**",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "In AI/language-model terms, a **token substrate** and an **embedding space** are different layers of representation.\n\n| Concept | What it is | Type of representation |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The underlying token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, sequence structure, rules for splitting text | **Discrete / symbolic** |\n| **Embedding space** | The learned vector space where tokens or concepts are represented as numerical vectors | **Continuous / geometric** |\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nText: \"unhappiness\"\n\nTokenizer / token substrate:\n[\"un\", \"happiness\"] or [\"un\", \"happy\", \"ness\"]\n↓\nToken IDs:\n[403, 9127, 1821]\n\nEmbedding space:\n403  → [0.12, -0.44, 0.91, ...]\n9127 → [-0.31, 0.08, 0.27, ...]\n1821 → [0.55, -0.19, -0.72, ...]\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** decides what the units are and how they are represented as discrete tokens.  \nThe **embedding space** gives those tokens numerical positions that the model can compute with.\n\nA useful analogy:\n\n- **Token substrate** = alphabet, vocabulary, grammar of the representational system\n- **Embedding space** = a semantic map where items are placed according to learned relationships\n\nSo if the token substrate says:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" = token 5678\n\"dog\" = token 9821\n\"table\" = token 4412\n```\n\nthen the embedding space may place `\"cat\"` and `\"dog\"` near each other because they are semantically related, while `\"table\"` may be farther away.\n\nIn short:\n\n> The **token substrate** is the discrete layer that defines and carries tokens.  \n> The **embedding space** is the continuous vector layer where those tokens acquire learned meaning and relationships.",
    "In language-model terms, **token substrate** and **context window** refer to different things:\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The underlying token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, and sequence format | Defines what the model’s input units are |\n| **Context window** | The maximum number of tokens the model can process or “see” at once | Defines how much tokenized input the model can use at one time |\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nText:\n\"The cat sat on the mat.\"\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** determines how that text becomes tokens:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \" on\", \" the\", \" mat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nor token IDs:\n\n```text\n[791, 3797, 7731, 389, 279, 5634, 13]\n```\n\nThe **context window** determines how many such tokens can fit into the model’s working input.\n\nFor example, if a model has a **context window of 8,000 tokens**, then it can consider up to roughly 8,000 tokens at once. If the conversation or document exceeds that, some content must be truncated, summarized, retrieved selectively, or otherwise managed.\n\nA simple analogy:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the language’s letters/words and how they are encoded\n- **Context window** = the size of the page or workspace the model can look at\n\nSo:\n\n> The **token substrate** defines the discrete units the model operates on.  \n> The **context window** defines how many of those units the model can process at once.\n\nThey are related because the context window is measured in **tokens**, but they describe different layers of the system.",
    "In language-model terms, **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different layers of the model’s processing.\n\n| Concept | What it is | Representation type | When it exists |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The discrete token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, sequence structure | **Discrete / symbolic** | Before model computation |\n| **Latent representation / hidden states** | Internal numerical activations produced by the model while processing tokens | **Continuous / vector-valued** | During model computation |\n\nExample pipeline:\n\n```text\nText:\n\"The cat sat.\"\n\nToken substrate:\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \".\"]\n↓\nToken IDs:\n[791, 3797, 7731, 13]\n↓\nEmbeddings:\nvectors for each token\n↓\nHidden states / latent representations:\ncontextual internal vectors at each model layer\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** defines the units the model receives:\n\n```text\n\" cat\" = token ID 3797\n```\n\nBut a **hidden state** is the model’s internal representation of that token in context.\n\nFor example, the token `\"bank\"` may have the same token ID in both sentences:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n\"The boat reached the river bank.\"\n```\n\nBut its **hidden states** will differ because the surrounding context changes its meaning.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the fixed/discrete input layer\n- **Hidden states** = dynamic/context-sensitive internal representations\n- **Latent representation** = a broader term for internal compressed or abstract representations the model forms\n\nA useful analogy:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the words printed on a page\n- **Hidden states** = the reader’s evolving understanding of those words in context\n\nIn short:\n\n> The **token substrate** defines what the model’s symbols are.  \n> The **hidden states / latent representations** are what the model internally computes from those symbols."
  ],
