        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** refer to different stages in how a model processes language.\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete input layer: the system that turns text into tokens the model can operate on.\n\nIt includes:\n\n- Tokenizer\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Tokenization rules\n- Special tokens\n- The ordered sequence of tokens\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The cat sat\" → [\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\"] → [791, 3797, 3332]\n```\n\nThis is still a symbolic/discrete representation.\n\n---\n\n### Latent representations / hidden states\n\n**Latent representations** or **hidden states** are the internal continuous vectors the model computes while processing those tokens.\n\nAfter token IDs are embedded and passed through transformer layers, each token position gets a changing vector representation.\n\nExample, schematically:\n\n```text\nToken ID 3797 → embedding vector → layer 1 hidden state → layer 2 hidden state → ... → final hidden state\n```\n\nA hidden state might encode information like:\n\n- The token’s meaning in context\n- Its grammatical role\n- Relations to other tokens\n- Long-range dependencies\n- Task-relevant abstractions\n\nFor example, the hidden state for `\"bank\"` will differ in:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\n\"I sat by the river bank.\"\n```\n\nThe token ID may be the same, but the hidden state becomes context-dependent.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete | Continuous |\n| Where it appears | Input/tokenization level | Inside the neural network |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, sequence structure | Contextual vectors computed by model layers |\n| Context-sensitive? | Usually no; token ID is fixed | Yes; changes based on surrounding tokens |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `3797` | vector representing `\"cat\"` in this specific sentence |\n| Role | Defines the units the model reads | Encodes what the model infers about those units |\n\n---\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nIf the model is reading a sentence:\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the printed words on the page.\n- The **hidden states** are like the reader’s evolving understanding of those words as the sentence unfolds.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate defines the discrete pieces of input.  \n> Hidden states are the model’s internal, contextual interpretations of those pieces.\n\nIn short: **tokens are what the model starts with; hidden states are what the model computes from them.**",
