        "assistant": "In language-model terms, **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different layers of the model’s processing.\n\n| Concept | What it is | Representation type | When it exists |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The discrete token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, sequence structure | **Discrete / symbolic** | Before model computation |\n| **Latent representation / hidden states** | Internal numerical activations produced by the model while processing tokens | **Continuous / vector-valued** | During model computation |\n\nExample pipeline:\n\n```text\nText:\n\"The cat sat.\"\n\nToken substrate:\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \".\"]\n↓\nToken IDs:\n[791, 3797, 7731, 13]\n↓\nEmbeddings:\nvectors for each token\n↓\nHidden states / latent representations:\ncontextual internal vectors at each model layer\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** defines the units the model receives:\n\n```text\n\" cat\" = token ID 3797\n```\n\nBut a **hidden state** is the model’s internal representation of that token in context.\n\nFor example, the token `\"bank\"` may have the same token ID in both sentences:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n\"The boat reached the river bank.\"\n```\n\nBut its **hidden states** will differ because the surrounding context changes its meaning.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the fixed/discrete input layer\n- **Hidden states** = dynamic/context-sensitive internal representations\n- **Latent representation** = a broader term for internal compressed or abstract representations the model forms\n\nA useful analogy:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the words printed on a page\n- **Hidden states** = the reader’s evolving understanding of those words in context\n\nIn short:\n\n> The **token substrate** defines what the model’s symbols are.  \n> The **hidden states / latent representations** are what the model internally computes from those symbols.",
